Sure this is how I would probably do it:

If you're feeling an emotion about yourself, what desire is creating that emotion? (Note that emotions are equal to desires)

Anxiety is felt as fear, for example. Fear of the future. So there is a desire to avoid the future, whatever type of future that is.

Fundamentally what should be asked is: What are you imagining about yourself, which is creating the desire to avoid that imagination about yourself? 

Here's an example of an answer to that which identifies the imagination about yourself and the desire it creates:

"I am imagining myself working tomorrow which gives me anxiety because it creates the desire to avoid work"

Then once you identify what you're imagining about yourself and what desire it creates, like the above statement, then this is where you actually start questioning how you relate to that desire. Where do "you" fit in? Like this:

Why am I able to fear something that hasn't happened yet? What kind of desire is my imagination of myself creating? How is it possible to desire to avoid an imagination of myself? etc.

Questioning where "you" fit in should make you eventually realize that "you" actually don't fit in at all. And the only thing you were ever desiring was your current self. The end.

I've caught myself in moments of irritation, and I think what I find is that thinking and communicating actually takes up a lot of energy, and if you observe it I think it the frustration is really about all the energy it is taking up from you. It's like a desire to help or communicate, but objectively and tangibly there's not enough energy anymore, so the priority switches up. It is essentially all just your desire, the "switch up" is like a preventative measure to prevent you from further "harming" yourself by spending energy on it. Logically you want to think and help more, but the anger cuts through that logic and says "no just leave." Anger seems to serve that function as an emotion, where it overrides what you logically want to do or accomplish in the future because you are being harmed presently.

What you said about being in close proximity to the situation rings true to me, because I think that makes it relevant to your direct experience of yourself, which causes you to obsess over the problem (thinking) in order to solve it, which puts you in a lot of contemplation. 

But I have to be honest when I say I don't have a solid reference for "dealing with intense relationships" as of now but in the past I certainly did lol. maybe i'll update you in the future. 

I definitely still contemplate and think a lot in general though, much less to do with me in past and future though.

You actually don't have to fear something or imagine something in order to avoid it. You just need to know what it leads to.

Maybe it's not accurate to say that the fear vanishes, but the imagined fear does. The knowledge of what it leads to stays. In the same way that you don't imagine yourself getting robbed in order to fear getting robbed. The fear only comes up when it physically happens because that is the only time you really need it.

You essentially keep the desire for everything you love, but skimmed off is the "opposite end" of that desire where you imagine yourself in the undesired scenario. It's like winning the lottery, and then going "dont i need to imagine myself losing this money in order to care about keeping the money I just earned"? No, all you need is the love for that money you earned.

> it makes a crazy amount of sense, but it feels like i somehow just attach to the idea of "oh my god that sounds so great i wanna turn myself into that" and then you just have the cycle going

it wouldnt affect your ability to become SR, but it would help identify certain beliefs about yourself. Like if you had something happen in childhood which created a certain belief. But it is entirely possible to not even think about that belief and still become SR while inquiring about some other belief. its not the specific belief about yourself that matters, even if it is a deep trauma, it is examining the structure that guides all beliefs about yourself and realizing that structure doesnt really represent anything which is "you"

to summarize a bit, trauma therapy would be useful for identifying healthy relationships and toxic people and how they affect you and the world, but that would still technically be outside the realm of SR which is a very secular perception of "the me that went through all that isn't me." 

If there is a belief about yourself created from trauma, therapy would say "this belief is false and it was instilled into you from a young age, you aren't actually that", and it feels good to see it that way because it is 100% true that it isn't what you are. But what they don't really say is that no belief can be what you are. Therapy would focus on questioning all the experiences which shape that belief (environment, people, etc.), whereas self-inquiry would question the fundamental desire to create that belief in the first place. 

Not that therapy is useless, but it more so focuses on "how humans are affected by relationships to each other" rather than "what you are fundamentally" and then it's up to you if you feel that is relevant to you. Like as an example, if you feel some kind of trauma around your relationship prior to SR I think it's perfectly valid to seek therapy/counselling about it because that will potentially get you out of the relationship without having to wait for SR, for example.

Here's a more physical and external angle of inquiry that might be helpful for people:

There is a rock. The rock is made of stone, which has a certain appearance. If you did not have eyes to see that rock, there would be no such thing as the "appearance of a rock." The rock depends on your eyes to perceive it and your eyes depend on the rock for it to exist as something which can be perceived by your eyes. Thus, the rock and your eyes both mutually depend on each other to be perceived. Where is the space for a "self" to take ownership over the "seeing" or "perceiving" of the rock? Isn't it the case that the perception of the rock and the existence of the rock are the exact same physical occurrence?
